#Text=Lillie Goodisson
#Text=Lillie Elizabeth Goodisson ( née Price ; c.1860 - 10 January 1947 ) was a Welsh Australian nurse and a pioneer of family planning in New South Wales .
#Text=Goodisson was born in Holyhead , Wales .
#Text=She trained as a nurse and at age 19 married London physician Lawford David Evans .
#Text=Soon after they moved to Auckland , New Zealand , where they started a family .
#Text=The couple and their two children moved to Melbourne in 1895 , and in 1897 established in Myrnong private hospital at St. Kilda .
#Text=Her husband died in 1903 and thereafter she went to Western Australia where she met and married her second husband , Albert Elliot Goodisson in 1904 .

#Text=They lived in Geraldton until Albert Goodisson went to Batavia in September 1913 to receive treatment for an illness , he died in 1914 leaving little to his wife , she borrowed money from her friend Ivy Brookes and returned to Melbourne .
#Text=She was involved in patriotic causes during World War I , however her finances did not improve , and she took another loan from Brookes to establish a library at Elwood in Melbourne .
#Text=Debts and ill health forced its liquidation in 1924 .
#Text=Goodisson moved to Sydney to be with her daughter in 1926 .

#Text=She joined the Women 's Reform League and with Ruby Rich , Marion Louisa Piddington and Anna Roberts founded the Racial Improvement Society , which later ( 1928 ) became the Racial Hygiene Association of New South Wales . [ 1 ] [ 2 ] [ 3 ]
#Text=The association was involved in promoting sex education , preventing and eradicating venereal disease and the education of the public in eugenics . [ 4 ]
#Text=Goodisson served as general secretary for the association .

#Text=She advocated the selective breeding of future generations for the elimination of hereditary disease , and defects and campaigned unsuccessfully for the segregation and sterilization of the mentally deficient and for the introduction of pre-marital health examinations . [ 4 ]
#Text=Although Goodisson campaigned for her association 's eugenics goals , her main interests were in contraception and politics . [ 3 ]
#Text=The likely catalyst for her campaign interests was her husband 's death from general paralysis and derangement ( general paralysis of the insane ) a symptom of Tertiary Syphilis .
#Text=In 1932 Goodisson unsuccessfully stood for the seat of Newcastle as the Social Reform Party ’s candidate . [ 3 ]

#Text=In 1933 the association established a birth control clinic in Sydney which Goodisson described as the first in Australia ; however , Piddington had established a birth control clinic in Melbourne two years earlier . [ 3 ]
#Text=The clinic served married women , providing diaphragms so that unwanted pregnancies would not be terminated by illegal abortions .
#Text=The activities of the clinic were controversial ; it received government subsidies only to have them withdrawn .
#Text=Piddington 's Melbourne clinic was forced to close in 1943 when the rubber used to make diaphragms was needed for war efforts ; the Sydney clinic remained open . [ 3 ]

#Text=Goodisson remained active in the association until her death in 1947 ; however the organisation 's activities were greatly reduced during the war and did not regain momentum until the 1960s . [ 3 ]
#Text=In 1960 the association was renamed the Family Planning Association of Australia . [ 5 ]

#Text=Goodisson was also an active member of the National Council of Women of New South Wales , the Travellers ' Aid Society , the Good Film League of New South Wales , and the Sydney Health Week and Mental Hygiene Council .
